If you listen, above all, to the music as background and you will listen to it every day only for a while, as in the tram, then you will be enough with any mobile that plays.
Which practically gets any real cell phone.
You should not even be interested in the format in which the mobile or player plays the music.
The MP3 plays it all and practically all the music you get will be in this format.
It is among the most widespread and except for it the absolute majority of the devices play music in WMA format.
The least include the AAC format (format used by Apple company and its iPod).
The best mobiles also make it possible, for example, to buy music online.
It is enough by means of the mobile internet to visit the competent pages of the operator (or any other service provider) and buy a song or an album.
This service could by itself be a compelling argument for acquiring a mobile for music.
Unfortunately the offer of the operators is miserable and the majority is limited only to the topics of fleeting success of the radios.
Prices are also not the lowest.
However, in general, it is assumed that precisely this way of selling music (either by GSM, internet or wireless internet) in the future will dominate the music industry.
Most people always have a cell phone on them.
Whenever you want to hear something, you will find your phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player will be forgotten at home.
However, it still depends if you always carry headphones or, at least, handsfree.
If not, you can use an integrated player that has virtually every mobile even if it is at least one MP3 player.
Probably the biggest advantage for many mobiles with music will be their price.
The cheapest usually cost less than three thousand.
