The first virtual operator is already arriving, this year, in the Czech Republic.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is fairly developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
Probably won't be long before he gets here.
That Czech operators are one of the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobile.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ) which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is one of the most expensive in the whole Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming fees you will probably come to a paradoxical situation - for some customers of Czech mobile operators the SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper than if sent from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to fight.
We probably find this paradoxical, as we have three mobile networks and their high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to regret that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
Of this also the president of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), Pavel Dvořák, has already said that there is no place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classic operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be very difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
It is precisely the virtual operator's entry into the mobile telephony market that brought a marked drop in prices to which the classical operators also had to react.
At the same time, even before sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the British market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It was shown that there is room for such operators and that they can succeed.
Otherwise, there is no need to look for examples too far.
In February of this year we informed you about the release of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to obtain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
Moreover, behind Mobilking lies the Penta group which, apart from that, in the Czech Republic is the owner of U:fon.
The advantage of virtual operators lies in the possibility of concentrating on many more specific target groups.
In addition, for them to function effectively, they have far fewer customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry relatively large costs in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world this type of virtual operators usually profile with low costs - they offer cheap SMS calls and messages which however, is often counterbalanced with the supply of tighter services.
Thus, for example, Tesco mobile in Britain offers SMS at least half as cheap compared to the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows can be a good blow also the bet for a trivial nothing target group.
This operator specifically addresses the man.
"The right man chooses Mobilking - he is the operator he likes and who he can trust," says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as that of Poland could engage in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čenický doubted this: "The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
Moreover, from the point of view of the supply of services, it is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be any virtual operator in the Czech Republic that will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather it is the launch of Mobilking in other countries of our region," said in telephone conversation for mobile.cz, Jana Studničková, spokesperson for the financial group Penta.
Indirectly he said that current mobile phone operators in the Czech Republic definitely do not bow to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible to ensure that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator already shows this the group GTS Novera that would like to take a step forward to become a real competition of Telefónica O2 in the field of clients of companies.
"We have a great interest in this, in order to offer our customers not only fixed telephony services but also mobile telephony services.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have met repeatedly with all Czech mobile phone operators.
With some of them we have made progress in the meetings," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
Then maybe they flash better times.
It appears that, by unofficial information, the first official operator would have to arrive possibly by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we believe that the situation is ideal for the appearance of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
So far no one has addressed us with some complex and serious project in this field," said Vlastimil Sršeň, spokesperson for Telefónica O2.
Other operators refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokesman Martina Kemrová, in exceptional accordance with O2's opinion, adds: "Until today we have not registered any viable commercial project that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop."
He adds, "In the T-Mobile network it will be difficult to find a virtual operator until the end of the year.
At this moment we should already have on the table some concrete contract that could be studied on such short horizon"
Vodafone's focus is rather on meeting the requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav Čenický adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this is as far as the sharing of costs and infrastructure is concerned.
We regard it as the greatest contribution from the point of view of the customers.
Vodafone's main strategy in this field lies in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on the mobile."
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition leading to a fall in prices and thus a fall in profits.
Then why facilitate entry into the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull the same rope, proof of that is the grab when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on the ČTU was at the time of U:fon's entry by the T-Mobile society.
This is attested to by public information available on the ČTÚ websites.
But precisely now U:fon serves as an argument why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová adds to this: "In addition, the competitive environment in the mobile telephony market has not long been open to a fourth operator.
As far as the character of the mobile telephony market in the Czech Republic is concerned, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would mean for him and, above all, for his services great requirements."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
This is not just the position of ČTU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tendering, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Tenders (UOHS).
However, it expressed its typical position on this issue.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile telephony market would be possible after an agreement was concluded on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator.
Until today no agreement has been closed since the offer of potential stakeholders was not interesting enough for the classic operators," added Kristián Chalupa, from the ÚOHS External Relations Department, to our question.
These statements are no surprise to the representatives of the operators.
For the offices that should represent the interests of consumers, this is more than just a consideration, apart from that, they should note that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Out there where virtual operators operate normally we can observe that their entry into the market contributed to the fall in prices of mobile telephony services"
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of market means and the lowering of prices does not fall within the interest of the ÚOHS.
The dramatic shock in this whole case really lies in the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether this is really a coincidence is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline at gas stations because it is clearly the work of chance and a hard fight for competition.
"The Office has found no signs of unfair competition in this regard and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, therefore they do not have a corresponding promotion of responsibility in their market actions.
The tools needed to open the mobile telephony market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecommunication regulators," added Chalupa to his response.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many conflicting points.
There is clearly an analysis of relevant markets developed by ČTÚ according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering a single market.
In this type of market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However some of the legal experts offer another vision - for a virtual operator to emerge the agreement with the network administrator is always necessary.
And the mobile operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument was not accepted, at least for ÚOHS it should be a warning that three mobile operators rise strikingly similarly.
Current complaints from stakeholders (including the GTS Novera company) show that in all negotiations with operators there are many similar impediments.
Placing responsibility on ČTU is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which ÚOHS washes its hands in this whole matter.
We've met him already in some similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law to extend the competence of ČTÚ in the field of commercial tendering was recently tabled but was not implemented, even though a number of specialists promised that the situation would improve.
The representatives of ÚOHS must know this perfectly well, but it is clear that their interests are elsewhere.
Everything's fine, when no one looks
At the same time, something like a pseudo-virtual operator continues to operate unnoticed and a few already exist in Czech mobile networks.
They are companies that put their own prices to mobile telephony services which, however, only a part are public.
These are usually companies that engage in multilevel marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile phone services.
Normally only a few chosen get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business client of the same ordering a lot of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that commercial conditions in all Czech mobile phone operators prohibit such resale.
"If cases such as those cited were discovered, one could talk about breach of contract terms that could result in the end of collaboration with the given company," answered the question about this problem Martina Kemrová.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile phone operators would not reach responsible people.
It is precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned above that they can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators is against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they make a profit that is not despicable and, at the same time - unlike the real virtual operators - in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čenický warns us of possible problems: "The law allows for speculation of this kind, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible percentage of customers.
They must also accept that the SIM card on their phone is not in their name, so they cannot dispose of it as a normal customer of the operators."
This is precisely what should seem to the ČTÚ minimally strange.
There is also a new question for the ÚOHS.
If mobile phone operators lock their eyes on this type of procedure, why block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the ÚOHS has sufficient competence to discover this type of activity and if it is not going to want it it should not be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that its commercial conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As was already clear in the text, the virtual operator's entry into the mobile telephony market brought a significant drop in service prices.
At the same time, virtually in all the countries where the virtual operator emerged, classical operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this irruption.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulatory bodies have now intervened and in none of the cases have they defended the operators but their customers.
Whether with formal measures or informal pressure they managed to get the first virtual operator to emerge and with it others began to emerge.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body has this whole case as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience, we cannot fail to be impressed that the confusion of powers in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator actually reaches these lands, then the Czech mobile market will probably start moving again.
If any of the operators let in a virtual mobile phone operator, it will be difficult for the ÚOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other stakeholders.
And we will perhaps stop calling more expensive than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best
Listen to the four presentations of the new version of the official Czech anthem.
On Sunday, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek on the occasion of the official Czech celebrations presented the new official recording of the anthem Where, my home.
The new anthem was recorded by the National Theatre orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
Four versions are available - two versions that are Solos, one male voice and one female voice, one with Choir and another instrumental.
The singing is done by Kateřina Knřínková and Adam Plachetka.
The authors of the anthem arrangements are Otakar Jeremiš and Jaroslav Krček.
On the iHNed.cz server you can listen to all four versions.
Bělohlávek considers this Czech national song one of the most beautiful hymns.
Czech Radio already said earlier that it intentionally chose for Solo singers with representatively young voices that are more expressive and popular.
"From the beginning I have tried with the two and then, also, with the Choir to look at the diction so that the text would be well understood, so that it would be consistent," he commented.
The official Czech anthem celebrates its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Where, my Home first played in 1834 on the tables of the State Theatre in Josef Kajetán Tyl's original Czech play Fidlovačka and arranged with the music of František Škroup.
It gained popularity and people made it theirs.
The first stanza of the song after the emergence of Czechoslovakia in 1918 became, naturally, a part of the official anthem.
One of the seven official symbols remained even after the emergence of the independent Czech Republic.
