The MHD in Prague takes us on Wednesday for the first time with the chip
On Wednesday, October 1, 2008, it is written in the history of the Prague Transport Company the date when the first passengers enter the metro, tram and bus with an electronic voucher in their pockets instead of a paper ticket.
This can now be purchased by nearly one hundred thousand people who own the Opencard chip card.
Passengers can purchase the 30-day, 90-day and annual voucher (this will be valid from 1 January 2009) and simultaneously load it on their chip card at the infocentres and stations of the transport company at Metro stations, Muzeum, M
Bonds can already be purchased from yesterday on the internet on the pages of the transport company, www.dpp.cz.
The service, until the afternoon, was used by more than 400 people.
Those who start using the internet as a form of commerce can definitely start to forget about the ticket stalls at subway stations, where until now they had to regularly queue up to take out a normal ticket.
The bonus is purchased online, and the Opencard card is charged to one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
"In these places there is at the disposal of the passengers a window with trained personnel that helps those interested with the purchase online and also with the reloading of the voucher purchased on their card," said the project spokesman, Martin Opatrný.
Apart from the library, it will also be possible to recharge the electronic voucher at the Opencard on the automatic vending machines found in some metro halls.
What are these vending machines like?
They are red, they remind us of a ticket-picking machine and the passengers will probably already have noticed them in the stations of the metro of Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are now five in the city but by the end of the year there should be eighty," Opatrný said.
The bonus is controlled by the machine instead of the driver
The use of the machine, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Simply enter in it the Opencard chip card and the previously paid bonus will be charged only on it.
Electronic bonds from tomorrow are valid not only in the capital but also in its surroundings.
That is to say, on the bypass trains and bus lines from the numbers 300 to 499 used mainly by the inhabitants of the towns of central Bohemia.
"On the trains attached to the integrated transport of Prague there are reviewers equipped with a reading card that will help confirm the validity of the time and the area of the voucher", explained the control of the tickets, Filip Drápal of the organization Ropid that establishes the schedules of the collective transport of Prague.
Ringbuses have their reading cards mounted in the driver's locker.
When entering it is necessary not only to show the card to the driver but also to accompany him with the Opencard in the place intended for it on the side of the Fund.
With this, the driver controls the validity of the voucher.
"If the passenger needs to verify the validity of the bonuses there is nothing easier than asking the driver for this information," Drapal said.
Passengers who do not travel on bypass buses and do not remember when it is they end the validity of the voucher can go to the vending machines where the cards are recharged.
Here, on the machine screen, you will be shown information about the validity of your document.
