The German Günther Bauer alternates in "Flamenco-people" the theatricality of some stagings with singers, dancers and guitarists with that less known side of these masters.
With this proposal, the photographer collects the particular iconography of flamenco from different areas.
Included in the program of the Month of Flemish Photography, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco-people" "can be any people but, seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not the typical images of artists on stage.
These people portrayed "in the street" are artists capable of transmitting on stage passion, sadness, joy... captivating the public.
To capture the personality of these artists, you don't have to take pictures of the stage.
They carry their personality and character inside.
What I was interested in was creating an intimate atmosphere that would allow me to capture with the camera the personality of the greats of flamenco."
With the flavor of the festival "Cante de las Minas", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to portray the singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, due to the selection of the camera and the material, recall classical photography.
The application of different stylistic media breaks with the classical base of the image, conferring modernity on it, an idea that reflects Bauer himself's understanding of flamenco: "A music with very traditional roots, which evolves and surprises every day".
It is not the action of dancing, singing or playing itself, but the personality of the artist, his character, which captivates the public with his art.
The search for an encounter with the essential, with the goblin that becomes visible in a way of feeling, of being and of being are and have been the constant of this work that is presented these days in the gallery El Photómata.
Known flamenco figures such as Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, configure this selection of almost seventy artists photographed.
The project has become an anthology of flamenco, which will soon be published in a book that will collect the portraits displayed in the exhibition.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with "Portraits of veteran athletes" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco-people", the photographer admits that "I love to portray people, to meet them and to be able to enter a moment in their life, be it a long or short moment.
I think that within photography portrait is the most difficult genre.
You meet or confront people, characters, who sometimes don't know, or who leave you just a few minutes to take the picture.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true."
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco, entitled "Flamenco-people", is exhibited at the Galería El Photómata, located at number 20 on Calle de la Mata, parallel to the Alameda de Hercules, where you can visit it until the 16th of October.
