Talking asleep
Some kids talk at night.
I'm not talking about those who wake up very wide-eyed by telling us something that happened the day before, but children who talk while asleep.
The first time it happens maybe you're scared, but it doesn't really matter.
It is a benign sleep disorder called somniloquis.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one has been told he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in life, for example, associated with an episode of high fever), or more regularly (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines their occurrence.
They are often related to other sleep disturbances such as nightmares, night terrors, nighttime enuresis (beeping asleep) or sleepwalking, but it doesn't have to be like this.
As mentioned above, they can also be associated with very high fever, stress or overexcitation situations.
Anyway, it's a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
He may speak in a quiet tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or the opposite (screams, cries, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be useful to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any question that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives him exit in this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress condition).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child much before going to sleep.
Therefore look for quiet games and avoid programs or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With very nervous children who find it hard to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain internal calm.
This will help the child to have a quieter sleep.
Once the somniloquia appear, try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember anything that has happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It's useless, because he's not conscious, and you'll break his dream.
Even if he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if you are very distressed during several episodes, you should consult or find out what causes so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most usual), do not fall into the temptation to ask him an interrogation to extract information from him.
You will get nothing, because being asleep is not conscious enough to organize his thought.
Moreover you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming to say that, with which much care is taken in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions that you draw.
Never tell the child that you can question him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even kidding.
That creates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don't worry, it's nothing bad, it's an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
