The interview - Blood is safe again
Hema-Québec celebrated yesterday its 10th anniversary of its foundation, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has once again been one of the safest and most effective providers of blood in the world.
And above all, he regained the public's confidence that had been seriously wavered by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
Faced with this drama and public discontent, the government of Canada conducted a public survey in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which sought to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations that such a disaster should no longer occur.
While Judge Krever was slow to present his relationship, certain provinces then set up a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of reports from Gélineau and Krever, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to provide Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and territories.
" In 1998, when Héma-Québec began her activities, almost 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Having made many efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work during the years that followed, we have regained public confidence ", he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94% of the Quebec population now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that " trust is extremely fragile " .
Since its establishment on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we attended in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says Décary.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted through the blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations in the reports of Krever and Gélineau, according to which when we do not know and when a serious illness can emanate from that, in this case the Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease that is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we put in place measures of exclusion.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had stayed in the United Kingdom for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been proven beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode thus showed us that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense. "
A much more sensitive HIV screening technique appeared on the market in 1999: Nucleid acid tests that make it possible to detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus and not the presence of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
Nucleid acid tests allowed the period to be shortened between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
We were able to reduce this period by less than one week.
We thus substantially reduce the risk that certain donors will be infected without knowing it and that we will not be able to detect them.
These improvements led to a significant reduction in the risk of contracting AIDS through a blood transfusion.
Today, one person every 12 million is at risk of receiving HIV-contaminated blood.
"That means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
As Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I think you can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion today to recover your health without worry," says the head of the management of Héma-Québec.
" Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, as an example of the western Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," Dr. Décary said before stressing that, in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide for adequate supplies.
" The needs increase because the population ages.
Since more aggressive cancer treatments, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The ageing of the population also has consequences for the network of blood donors which groups on average only 3% of Quebeces eligible for blood donation. "
All people in good health, 18 years old and who meet the eligibility criteria can however donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who propose their blood are not accepted, because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travel to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
The hardships are very rare.
But the members of this network of donors need to be renewed as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it is difficult to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain it and encourage them to be a regular donor.
Since today's life is very rampant, we rarely find the time to spend an hour donating his blood," Francine Décary grieves.
With a budget of $297 million a year, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eye balloons and skin that is almost exclusively used for the large burned ones.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public umbilical cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was formerly considered as biomedical waste is filled with a blood rich in stem cells that can be used for the treatment of serious diseases such as leukemia.
" We celebrated a few weeks ago the placing on the bench of our thousandth blood sample of the umbilical cord and it is expected to take out more than a thousand of these per year.
We would have to start proposing it for grafts at the beginning of next year ", explains Dr. Décary who describes this cord blood-taking program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot enjoy this ", as Héma-Québec does not have the resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
