Wall Street Rescue Operation - Democrats and Republicans Agree
The Bush administration and the leaders of Congress, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached agreement yesterday on the most important economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
The new version of the $700 billion plan that aims to curb the financial crisis that has shaken Wall Street for months has yet to be confirmed by both Houses of Congress.
It provides in particular for better monitoring by the elected parties of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money invested, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized from non-payment, as well as a right of control over the salaries paid to the leaders of the companies assisted.
The American Secretary of the Treasury, Henry Paulson, the Speaker of the House of Representatives, Nancy Pelosi, and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news a few minutes after midnight, yesterday, at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We made great progress towards an agreement that will be effective in the markets," said Bush administration representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done to cover up the economy and ordinary Americans in the face of the current crisis on Wall Street," the Democrat explained.
"It's the fundamental point: if we don't do this, trauma, chaos and disruptions on the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
The negotiations had ended very quickly in the last few hours because they feared the effect that a new failure in the mood of investors would cause.
The last hour they had set was the opening of markets this morning.
The two candidates in the American presidential elections, who have late joined the negotiations, were rather favorable to the agreement, not forgetting however to squeeze their discontent of being forced to reach this limb.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama was given certain provisions to reach the agreement, particularly the one that would allow the owners to retain their domicile and the one on the wages of the leaders of the surviving companies by the state.
" When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary action because of the irresponsibility of some, there is no need to be congratulated.
But these measures are necessary," he commented on American television.
His Republican adversary, John McCain, Interrogated on another network to see if he would vote for the proposed plan, replied that: "I would like to see the details, but I hope to vote for it."
" The important points I read [show] that it is something that we will have to digest and with which we will be able to advance.
He said the option of doing nothing is not acceptable."
The 700 billion plan aims to buy with taxpayers' money the dubious debts, the risky and unsaleable assets of American financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis caused by the outbreak of a housing bubble that first led to the sinking of risk mortgage credits before extending to other more common forms of credit securities (PCAA) and causing a liquidity freeze and a sluggishness of banks and financial institutions.
It's a group of Republicans elected that had changed the first draft agreement, last week.
We believe that we have emerged from the impasse since the Democrats accepted that certain "toxic" assets of companies in difficulty are only secured by the government, rather than purchased.
In order to smooth out the roughness for everyone in Congress, we also added a provision that stipulated that if the government had to make losses for five years with this program, it could impose new fees that would aim to help it recover money.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first part of 250 billion to which a further 100 billion may be added if the president deems it necessary.
