What did they produce at the Zuschlag &amp; Co. invoice factory?
Very soon, on 8 October, criminal proceedings will begin against János Zuschlag and his accomplices.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of committing frauds of significant damage, in a business way, continuously and in an organized manner in addition to other crimes, including the falsification of documents.
According to the Office of the Prosecutor, they used the funds obtained in the public tenders for their own purposes, often justifying the performance of the tasks with false invoices.
The public funds and that of the municipalities - in their entirety some 65 million HUF - stopped in part in the treasury of the organisation Fiatal Baloldal and in part in the pocket of private persons.
The method, which was also made known by the investigators, was to justify the collection of funds obtained in public competitions with false invoices behind which there was no actual execution, the different associations never fulfilled their obligations assumed.
According to the prosecution, most of the invoices were false.
For this purpose they obtained the checkbooks in the Józsefváros District market and the circular stamps were manufactured in the town of Kiskunhalas.
And the question that on behalf of which company the forged invoice was to be made was decided among others on that tour of the Upper Balaton Region where János Zuschlag sent István Sides.
The latter confessed that for this purpose he had to choose hostels and restaurants.
He asked for an invoice for his consumption and these served as a model for drawing up the invoices they presented, among others, in the competitions of the Ministry of Youth and Sports Affairs, in the Ministry of Social and Labour Affairs, as well as in the City of the Capital.
These invoices were signed mostly by István Lados and his accomplice András
During one of his "study trips" Sides chose a brewery.
According to two invoices issued in 2003 by Zuschlag and his accomplices, this gastronomic center provided food for a group of ninety people from the Biztos Pont Egyesület Association.
However - according to the center manager - so many people do not fit at the same time in that place.
Similarly, the invoice issued in summer 2002 for the Jobb Jövőért Foundation - later called Együtt to Harmadik Évezredért - was full of formal and contextual errors.
As a hostel in Badacsonytomaj had only three rooms and more than ten people could not stay there in one night, however on the bill there were one hundred and thirty people.
But the manufacturers of big fantasy invoice also exaggerated when they pointed to the gastronomic center Pigal Kft. because in the book store of the same - according to the information given to the Prosecutor's Office - there were no documents in the name of Jobb Jövőért and Hoppá.
