Overlay psychology: Why do we spend more money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York discovered the neurological - economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in Science magazine, people do not want to lose in competitions such as eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
Scientists attempted to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" by means of experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played lottery, the other participated in an auction and in the meantime the active areas of the brain of the people involved in the experiment were examined through the functional magnetic resonance system (fMRI).
In both games the participants could earn money, but during the auctions, where it is fundamental to bet more than the other, when losing the game the functioning of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex was intensified.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the "self prize" mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in betting is explained as a prevention so as not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To base their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment three groups bet against one person under different circumstances.
The control group was simply informed of the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
In addition to that, another group was promised that if they won, they would receive an additional $15 prize.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction the members of the group lost even that money.
Thus the only difference between the two groups was that for one triumph was highlighted and for the other failure.
However, by checking the hypothesis of the neurologists, the members of the group who played "against failure" were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the "winner" group.
"These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
For those so far explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only visual neurological methods helped to resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so now we come to a third explanation" - established Andrew Schotter, professor of the faculty of economics at the University of New York.
Hepatitis: When should you go to your doctor?
Around 500 million people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of infected people in this country is estimated at 100,000, but only 7,000 are treated because many of the sick do not know that they are infected.
Hepatitis is the common name of different liver diseases caused by viruses.
Symptoms are very similar; liver infection and jaundice are characteristic, but their pathogens and diseases are very different.
Hepatitis viruses dependent on the pathogen are spread by two main forms: hepatitis A and E via food (e.g. with water or infected food), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body moods (sperm, vagina humor, saliva).
Travelers are advised to protect themselves by means of a vaccine against the A and B virus, against C there are no vaccines.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifests by a general poor condition, weakness, abdominal pain, and nausea.
After this, jaundice appears in the skin and in the white of the eyes, the excrement becomes clear, the dark-colored urine and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year, one million people die in cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected patients receives pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can cause liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most people who are infected do not know that they are ill because this pathological agent gradually destroys liver cells and many times the first symptoms only appear 20-30 years later.
Premature examination, systematic medical monitoring is therefore very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusions before 1991, drug users and those who carry tattoos.
There are now some 200 million people in the world suffering from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with a routine laboratory control as well, it is worth consulting the family doctor when experiencing any unknown symptoms.
The disease is cured if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so you can suppress the infection and prevent the cancer.
September 30 is the World Day of Hepatitis, which was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its aim is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their early recognition.
Does it hurt less for those who believe in God?
According to the result of a recent investigation, religious faith has a calming effect that also alleviated the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed that religious belief in what way it influences human pain - reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
In the framework of this unique experiment they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while all were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the human brain scanning technique, it was possible to verify that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first in the series of researches in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University also participate.
The analysis occurred as follows; they fixed a sparkling instrument to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to fix their eyes on two paintings; the Virgin Mary, the work of 17th century Sassoferrato and the Lady of the Armiño of Leonardo da Vinci of the 15th century.
The researchers had the hope that the Virgin Mary's spectacle would provoke a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo's oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a reassuring effect.
The patients spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electric shocks in four successive parts during the period while observing the religious theme painting or the other.
Catholics stated that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as "protected" people, "they calmed down and peace reigned in their hearts."
When they looked at the religious theme picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so striking you can achieve a similar effect with atheists as well, you just have to find the right image.
"We should find the portrait of a person for whom they feel very positively, as for a mother or a father" - said the psychologist.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright celebrated the outcome of the investigation.
"The exercise of faith should and in many cases of truth changes our personality" - Wright added.
After these formidable results there remains a single question: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if Leonardo's Madonna or another painter of his stature were shown to the faithful?
Would the vision of a high quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
