This can happen because Google unlike Microsoft, does not ask users for any identification code, nor money for its applications, the code is open and the program package free, constantly updated and seems more youthful, more collaborative than the practice of the official software giant.
But it can also be because geeks see with precision the very problematic relationship between people's rights and the Internet that occurred precisely because of one of the key words most mentioned in recent years: the Web 2.0.
Web 2.0 is about collaboration, leaving intentional traces behind us and taking advantage of the communication channels available, and while the measures of these vary individually, the essence remains the same: showing ourselves.
A normal young person can have a profile on numerous collective pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and can even link them with other services, such as Twitter or last.fm that offers a list of their music customs, then include them in a tracking system such as the FriendFeed or the Blip.fm, can also have a blog, in which the most recent photo galleries that are stored on Flickr or Picasa automatically appear.
We can learn numerous cases from which it follows that for example the bride, seeing the flow of photographs the following morning from the common friends, learns with whom she spent the previous night her fraudulent boyfriend or can fire the employee of a company because he writes his sincere opinion on his blog about the management of the company: one thing is certain, the definition of private life was completely revalued.
The "on-line" life of a person is what she shows of herself - this is the definition that hides behind the conduct of today's youth.
And the one who wants to hide something, or at least pretends to dodge Google's monopoly, can do it (starting for example with the Scroogle that uses Google's search system, but leaves no trace).
There are many people who don't want to register on the collective pages to prevent them from finding them, but Google's "on-line" applications can be replaced, from text-writing software to image and news reading applications with alternative versions that don't connect to gigantic servers or prepare the most perfect profile about us.
Public opinion expects almost openly the day Google shows its true face.
The company with its current value of $156 billion is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion), AdWords/AdSense advertising surfaces threaten advertising agencies' revenues, while services that are increasingly introduced cause severe headaches not only for Microsoft, but also for numerous other software developers.
Critical observers, however, will find the contradictions alarming as well: for example the top management flatly rejected the protest of employees after doubling the price of the company's nursery, considered the unlimited number of employees' food too expensive, but all this is nothing compared to the fact that in 2006 Google gave in to the pressure of the Chinese government and the company according to the agreement leaked any information that violated the good morale and interests of the Chinese regime.
One of the company's internal regulations says they won't announce any new services in advance, but only when it's ready to run, what if it's certain is that the foreseeable problems of the coming months and years will be able to stir the world: while some believe that Google's book and magazine scanning and archiving project will acquire such dimensions that the company will soon be cited by the U.S. Supreme Court, others fear its Health system, because in it we can create our own complete health profile, with previous analyses, with our doctors and our problems.
And the fact that Google is going to create a genetic database, will provide a good raw material for science fiction writers, the Scroogled, novel of the popular Cory Doctorow, describes in Orwelian form that future, in which a man only of the data of Google can be described alarmingly well.
