Smart car mimics bumblebee flight
What would be the best method for developing technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of existing obstacle sensors in nature?
For example, bumblebees.
In a surprising project presented at CEATEC in Japan, bumblebees gave the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
The Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the BR23C-type robot steering system imitator of nature, which was given the characteristics of bumblebees, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can dodge all collisions.
During the flight each bumblebee creates its own particular oval space that actually looks a lot like our protective safety capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of RP and development and research.
The compound eyes of bumblebees that are able to see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees play an important role.
To copy the function of composite eyes, engineers used the laser length measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at an angle of 180 degrees, calculates its distance and sends a signal to the microprocessor of the vehicle that immediately transforms into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle imitating the movements of the bumblebees, modifies the direction by turning the wheels to the extent necessary.
Unlike any existing system at present, this maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If not, the robot of the vehicle could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the protective safety capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a bumblebee does to dodge other bumblebees.
This process should take place in the blink of an eye.
However, unlike bumblebees, movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonals, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of turning the wheels
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for bumblebees to dodge other bumblebees, here they only used as possibility for the robot of the car the rotational movement and the acceleration besides the braking.
The BR23C uses lythium-polymer batteries that are lighter and its energy density is higher, meaning that they have a longer lifetime than that of lythium-ion.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the processing capacity of the data, let alone the storage capacity.
This device in every second should only process some input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers, thus using only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No gigabyte memories are needed, no megabytes.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately avoid obstacles, which according to Nissan calculations, will be able to be incorporated into the models manufactured in series within ten years.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to his destination, avoiding obstacles in his way.
