A written version of the $700 billion financial bailout package law has been prepared and will be implemented in several phases to buy bad bank loans.
Half the money will be spent in the first phase.
According to Eastern Coast schedule during the new consultations that lasted until after midnight on Saturday, the leaders of the congress reached an agreement around the financial rescue package of 700 billion dollars in total, after several days of discussion - reported Reuters.
We have made significant progress - said Nancy Pelosi, Democratic President of the North American Congress, stating that the agreement needs to be formalized in just one document.
The compromise made on the package was supported by both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
Henry Paulson, the Minister of Finance, speaking about the outcome of the compromise said: this program will work and be efficient but other measures are needed. According to Pelosi, it is not about saving the Wall Street, but about turning the car of the economy.
The written version of the package was published before the opening of Asian markets, i.e. on Sunday before 8 p.m., according to Washington hours (i.e. before 2 a.m. on Monday, according to Central European times), without causing a spectacular jump in the bags.
On the bill called the 2008 Emergency Act for Economic Stabilization, the first Monday the American Congress will vote and then the Senate.
President George W. Bush on Saturday night consulted Pelosi and then the White House also held news about the deal.
We are happy with the progress made during the night and highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy - said Tony Fratto, the White House spokesman.
The program is different from the Bush administration's original proposal to spend all $700 billion to buy bad-quality credit fund securities.
Now you can only spend half of the $700 billion, using $250 billion immediately after Congress votes, probably on Monday, of this sum the Ministry of Finance will buy securities credit fund securities, of bad rating and the fate of another $100 billion depends on the president's decision.
This programme will be controlled by a special body, in which the president of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The other half of the $700 billion can be spent after a new Congressional decision.
According to the law the Ministry of Finance can apply a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy bad credits, mortgages and securities credit fund securities, as well as other "poisonous" type credits as well.
The purchase can be made at auctions or directly - reported competent persons of the ministry.
The law allows the companies concerned to participate in an insurance program where the financial portfolio guarantees the worrying elements, for which the companies will pay the amount corresponding to the foreseeable damages.
Henry Paulson said: the law thus ensures the necessary financial means, which can reach up to $700 billion to meet the urgent needs of the US financial system, be it the purchase of bad financial means, their insurance or the prevention of risks that could cause the collapse of some major financial institutions.
We do everything we need to be ready to introduce the law as soon as they sign it - he added.
On the other hand, the heads of the banks that are in distress and waiting for state aid will be able to count on the official limitation of their compensations, which the American slang calls simply gold parachute.
Only in certain cases will payments be limited, and limitations depend on the form of assistance from the Ministry of Finance.
The limitation means that if the ministry buys in the framework of an auction, an extra tax will be imposed on the gold parachutes, unless the failed chief of the bank retires.
By buying bad credits directly the government will aggressively intervene to ensure that the chiefs' compensations are not overstated.
In addition to the above, the existing gold parachute contracts are not to be changed, the limitations relate only to new contracts to stimulate participation in the programme as well.
This is the first case in American history that will be in force a legal limitation on the revenues of the directors general - commented the Democrat Barney Frank, president of the commission of Congress, responsible for the financial services.
The State will also have the right to acquire shares of the banks participating in the program, thus reducing the risk of taxpayers, since ultimately they will be able to even make profits with the transaction as soon as the economy recovers and with it the bank.
According to the bill in the next five years, the president will have to present a proposal to Congress on how to return financial sector losses to taxpayers.
Of course, reservations were expressed on both sides with regard to the draft.
This is not what the American citizens entrusted us with, that is, they are not protecting the taxpayers' dollars - declared the Republican Congressman of California, Darrell Issa.
His fellow Ohio Democrat, Mary Kaptur said: the measures urged it the same ones who are responsible for the collapse of Wall Street.
Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008 national industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month's prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007 prices - reported the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH).
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 percent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 percent compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 percent over the previous month and by 3.2 percent over the previous year.
Industrial sales prices rose by only a minimal measure, with 0.1 per cent.
The domestic sales prices of the processing industry sectors increased minimally, with 0.1 percent compared to July.
The biggest increase in price magnitude occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 per cent), due primarily to the 4.6 per cent monthly increase in bags and belts and the 2.5 per cent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical materials industry (1.6 per cent).
There was a price decrease in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 per cent), in the production of electrical machines and instruments (0.9 per cent), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 per cent).
The prices of paper manufacturing, publishing houses and printing presses did not change.
In the rest of the processing industry sectors, prices increased by 0.2 to 0.9 per cent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent an important weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 per cent was recorded in August, first as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from the first of July.
In a comparison of a period of twelve months - in the domestic sales of the processing industry sectors - the largest price increase was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 per cent).
In the metal processing sector, an increase of 13.2 per cent was observed, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of decisive weight, there was an increase of 11 per cent.
There was a decline in prices in the textile industry (2.5 per cent), as well as in the manufacture of electrical machines and instruments (0.3 per cent).
In the rest of the processing sectors the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 per cent.
Over the past year in the processing industry globally prices increased by 10.2 per cent.
Prices of electricity, gas, heat and water supply exceeded the previous year's prices by 18.7 per cent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the highest monthly price increase (0.7 per cent) was recorded in the sectors of investment goods.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, in energy and intermediate sector prices there was no change from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month last year, the biggest price increase occurred in the energy sectors and in the intermediary industry (16.8 per cent).
In consumer goods producing branches, there was a 6.8 per cent decline and in investment goods 1.4 per cent.
Industry export prices calculated at HUF increased by 1.1 percent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a 3.9 percent decrease.
The price of our national currency in a month fell by 1.7 percent compared to the euro and by 7.1 percent compared to the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 percent compared to the euro and 15.9 percent compared to the dollar.
