Járóka: The vicious circle of poverty and segregation must be broken
Today the European Summit for Equal Opportunities has begun in Paris, its host being France, which this year is also the current president of the European Union.
Lívia Járóka, deputy of the European People's Party for Fidesz, in her message to the plenary, as one of the main speakers of this professional meeting, drew attention to segregation in education, because it is one of the most serious violations that plague Gypsy children and is also the greatest obstacle to the prevalence of their interests.
This high-level conference was opened - on behalf of the French Presidency - by Xavier Bertrand, French Minister for Employment and Social Affairs and by Vladimir Spidla, European Commissioner responsible for jobs, social affairs and equal opportunities.
The meeting was attended by representatives of governments, European social partners and representatives of the most important European organisations for the protection of social rights.
Járóka - according to the press bureau of Fidesz's group of MEPs in the European Parliament - warned that in addition to discrimination in employment, Gypsies are left out of the labour market in the first place because of their low level of schooling.
"Most young Gypsies have not completed secondary education and due to the poor quality of basic education, only a negligible part can obtain a university diploma."
Járóka also stressed that education, as a fundamental human right, has a decisive role in the prevalence of other human rights as well.
Investing in the education of Roma children at an early age can strengthen the economy of the Member States of the European Union.
According to the MEP, there is a need to raise awareness of these issues among both Roma and non-Gypsies.
For the earlier a Gypsy student starts school, the more likely he will be to become an active member of the labour market; through income and consumer taxes they will also contribute to the national budget.
"Gypsies, as citizens of the European Union, must be guaranteed the right to quality education and guarantee the abolition of segregated and low-level education" - highlighted Lívia Járóka.
According to the MEP, the objective and active unity of the European Union is necessary in order to speed up school desegregation processes immediately, for this the correct compliance with existing and planned anti-discrimination directives is of fundamental importance.
"We must break the vicious circle of poverty, segregation and unemployment, we must offer Roma children the possibility that guarantees the democratic space so that they can contribute to the future of Europe as full citizens" - Járóka demanded.
The aim of the European Summit for Equal Opportunities organised annually since last year's Berlin meeting in the sign of the "European Year of Equal Opportunities" is to ensure a unique forum to promote the abolition of discrimination and equal opportunities at European and national level in the Member States.
