When the energy is born from the waves, the big ones come down to the stage
It is an exterminated site that occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface and is now being discovered by the world's largest energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides are the new renewable sources upon which the great ones look like Chevron.
The possibility of collecting energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years and in the 1970s along with the first oil crisis, investigations intensified.
When the price of low oil, in 1980, the idea of harnessing marine energy was set aside, but now that environmental cases and the new increase in oil give impetus to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London has estimated by 2007 that 15 percent of the world's electricity need could be covered by implants that exploit the movement of sea waves.
This amount would be twice the amount currently produced by nuclear power plants.
And besides, there would be currents and tides.
Giants to attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy has been Enersis, which in 2005 has sealed an agreement to build an implant in Northern Portugal.
When the intention was announced it seemed like a revolutionary step.
Two years away to bet on marine energy are always more and among these companies those who have always voted for traditional energy.
"Chevron is studying ocean energy technology – has declared the spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil colossus to the economic newspaper Wall Street Journal – and is assessing the possibility of cooperating with us."
The cooperation in question is about obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission to carry out a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
It is a fairly important sign, considering that in Alaska the US continues to extract oil and recently President Bush has activated a plan for further drilling.
In addition to Chevron is Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey to follow the path of energy coming from the sea, the total invested so far, although not detailed indicate an increasing interest.
Technology to develop.
Experts talk about a technology still at the beginning, because marine energy there is no doubt that it has a great environmental impact.
For now the impacts like those Portuguese or Scots are small in size and do not seem to create major problems for the ecosystem.
To produce energy on a long scale, a technology with a greater environmental impact must be used.
And the options are several: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of boas attached to each other.
The force of the waves, which causes the boas to move up and down becomes hydraulic pressure with pistons and cylinders inside them.
The pressure spins a turbine that in turn feeds a generator.
Electricity is sent to the coast through submarine cables.
For now there are four such implants under development, pending only federal approval, apart from energy, could serve a military facility.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, already produces power for a shopping mall and a parking lot, using underwater turbines in the East River of New York.
The movement of water when there are tides, spins the turbine pallets, creating a rotating movement that feeds the generator.
Verdant has said that it has a long cast of customers waiting for the necessary authorizations to use the energy.
After the waves, the tides.
A particular interest, they say in the Institute for the development of electric energy, merits at this time the potential of tides.
Although it is an intermittent phenomenon, tides are more preventable than wind, sun or waves and therefore more reliable as a source of energy.
It is above all about tidal energy that states such as New York, Maine and Alaska, together with others approaching the coasts, have invested $7.5 million in 2008 and an investment of $35 million is planned for 2009.
